SIMPLE: invert
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invert
<hw>In*vert"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Inverted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inverting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>invertere</ets>,
<ets>inversum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>vertere</ets> to
turn. See <er>Verse</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn over; to put upside down; to upset; to place
in a contrary order or direction; to reverse; <as>as, to <ex>invert</ex>
a cup, the order of words, rules of justice, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That doth <qex>invert</qex> the attest of eyes and ears,⟦br⟧
As if these organs had deceptious functions.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such reasoning falls like an <qex>inverted</qex> cone,⟦br⟧
Wanting its proper base to stand upon.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To change the position of; -- said
of tones which form a chord, or parts which compose harmony.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To divert; to convert to a wrong use.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Knolles.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To convert; to reverse; to
decompose by, or subject to, inversion. See <er>Inversion</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 10.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Invert
<hw>In*vert"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To undergo
inversion, as sugar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Invert
<hw>In"vert</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>Subjected to the process of inversion; inverted; converted; <as>as,
<ex>invert</ex> sugar</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Invert sugar</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a variety
of sugar, consisting of a mixture of dextrose and levulose, found
naturally in fruits, and produced artificially by the inversion of cane
sugar (sucrose); also, less properly, the grape sugar or dextrose
obtained from starch. See <er>Inversion</er>, <er>Dextrose</er>,
<er>Levulose</er>, and <er>Sugar</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Invert
<hw>In"vert</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Masonry)</fld> <def>An inverted
arch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invertase</ent>⟦br⟧
